{
  "texts": [
    "The key concept behind graph attention networks (GAT) is that different neighbors of a node possess distinct roles and levels of significance.",
    "Consequently, they contribute to the generation of the node embedding with varying weights, allowing for adaptive attention-based mechanisms to capture the importance of each neighbor in the embedding process.",
    "This network employs the multi-head attention mechanism to aggregate embeddings.",
    "The following formulas show how GAT computes the embeddings (Velickovic et al. 2017)",
    "where ∥ is the concatenation operator, K is the number of attention heads and vu is the attention coefficient between two nodes v and u."
  ]
}